Π. A. Suum: his head, as usual, covered with a veil. This costume had, doubtless, no deeper intention at first than the expression of old age in the personage represented, for we see the figure of Winter, the decrepit age of the Year, similarly clothed. Winckelmann, however, (P. G. de Stoech, p. 33) very sagaciously discovers in it an allusion to the fact mentioned by Macrobius (Sat. i. 10), that to Satura alone of the gods did people offer sacri- fice with annover-ed head.
